#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:1
msgid ""
"Assert that two numbers (or two sets of numbers) are equal to each other "
"within some tolerance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:4
msgid ""
"Due to the `intricacies of floating-point arithmetic`__, numbers that we "
"would intuitively expect to be equal are not always so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:7
msgid ""
">>> 0.1 + 0.2 == 0.3\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:12
msgid ""
"This problem is commonly encountered when writing tests, e.g. when making "
"sure that floating-point values are what you expect them to be.  One way to "
"deal with this problem is to assert that two floating-point numbers are "
"equal to within some appropriate tolerance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:17
msgid ""
">>> abs((0.1 + 0.2) - 0.3) < 1e-6\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:20
msgid ""
"However, comparisons like this are tedious to write and difficult to "
"understand.  Furthermore, absolute comparisons like the one above are "
"usually discouraged because there's no tolerance that works well for all "
"situations.  ``1e-6`` is good for numbers around ``1``, but too small for "
"very big numbers and too big for very small ones.  It's better to express "
"the tolerance as a fraction of the expected value, but relative comparisons "
"like that are even more difficult to write correctly and concisely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:28
msgid ""
"The ``approx`` class performs floating-point comparisons using a syntax "
"that's as intuitive as possible::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:31
msgid ""
">>> from pytest import approx\n"
">>> 0.1 + 0.2 == approx(0.3)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:35
msgid "The same syntax also works for sequences of numbers::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:37
msgid ""
">>> (0.1 + 0.2, 0.2 + 0.4) == approx((0.3, 0.6))\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:40
msgid "Dictionary *values*::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:42
msgid ""
">>> {'a': 0.1 + 0.2, 'b': 0.2 + 0.4} == approx({'a': 0.3, 'b': 0.6})\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:45
msgid "``numpy`` arrays::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:47
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as "
"np                                                          \n"
">>> np.array([0.1, 0.2]) + np.array([0.2, 0.4]) == approx(np.array([0.3, "
"0.6])) \n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:51
msgid "And for a ``numpy`` array against a scalar::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:53
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np                                         \n"
">>> np.array([0.1, 0.2]) + np.array([0.2, 0.1]) == approx(0.3) \n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:57
msgid ""
"By default, ``approx`` considers numbers within a relative tolerance of "
"``1e-6`` (i.e. one part in a million) of its expected value to be equal. "
"This treatment would lead to surprising results if the expected value was "
"``0.0``, because nothing but ``0.0`` itself is relatively close to ``0.0``. "
"To handle this case less surprisingly, ``approx`` also considers numbers "
"within an absolute tolerance of ``1e-12`` of its expected value to be "
"equal.  Infinity and NaN are special cases.  Infinity is only considered "
"equal to itself, regardless of the relative tolerance.  NaN is not "
"considered equal to anything by default, but you can make it be equal to "
"itself by setting the ``nan_ok`` argument to True.  (This is meant to "
"facilitate comparing arrays that use NaN to mean \"no data\".)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:69
msgid ""
"Both the relative and absolute tolerances can be changed by passing "
"arguments to the ``approx`` constructor::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:72
msgid ""
">>> 1.0001 == approx(1)\n"
"False\n"
">>> 1.0001 == approx(1, rel=1e-3)\n"
"True\n"
">>> 1.0001 == approx(1, abs=1e-3)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:79
msgid ""
"If you specify ``abs`` but not ``rel``, the comparison will not consider the "
"relative tolerance at all.  In other words, two numbers that are within the "
"default relative tolerance of ``1e-6`` will still be considered unequal if "
"they exceed the specified absolute tolerance.  If you specify both ``abs`` "
"and ``rel``, the numbers will be considered equal if either tolerance is "
"met::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:86
msgid ""
">>> 1 + 1e-8 == approx(1)\n"
"True\n"
">>> 1 + 1e-8 == approx(1, abs=1e-12)\n"
"False\n"
">>> 1 + 1e-8 == approx(1, rel=1e-6, abs=1e-12)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:93
msgid ""
"If you're thinking about using ``approx``, then you might want to know how "
"it compares to other good ways of comparing floating-point numbers.  All of "
"these algorithms are based on relative and absolute tolerances and should "
"agree for the most part, but they do have meaningful differences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:98
msgid ""
"``math.isclose(a, b, rel_tol=1e-9, abs_tol=0.0)``:  True if the relative "
"tolerance is met w.r.t. either ``a`` or ``b`` or if the absolute tolerance "
"is met.  Because the relative tolerance is calculated w.r.t. both ``a`` and "
"``b``, this test is symmetric (i.e.  neither ``a`` nor ``b`` is a "
"\"reference value\").  You have to specify an absolute tolerance if you want "
"to compare to ``0.0`` because there is no tolerance by default.  Only "
"available in python>=3.5.  `More information...`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:108
msgid ""
"``numpy.isclose(a, b, rtol=1e-5, atol=1e-8)``: True if the difference "
"between ``a`` and ``b`` is less that the sum of the relative tolerance w.r."
"t. ``b`` and the absolute tolerance.  Because the relative tolerance is only "
"calculated w.r.t. ``b``, this test is asymmetric and you can think of ``b`` "
"as the reference value.  Support for comparing sequences is provided by "
"``numpy.allclose``.  `More information...`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:117
msgid ""
"``unittest.TestCase.assertAlmostEqual(a, b)``: True if ``a`` and ``b`` are "
"within an absolute tolerance of ``1e-7``.  No relative tolerance is "
"considered and the absolute tolerance cannot be changed, so this function is "
"not appropriate for very large or very small numbers.  Also, it's only "
"available in subclasses of ``unittest.TestCase`` and it's ugly because it "
"doesn't follow PEP8.  `More information...`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:126
msgid ""
"``a == pytest.approx(b, rel=1e-6, abs=1e-12)``: True if the relative "
"tolerance is met w.r.t. ``b`` or if the absolute tolerance is met. Because "
"the relative tolerance is only calculated w.r.t. ``b``, this test is "
"asymmetric and you can think of ``b`` as the reference value.  In the "
"special case that you explicitly specify an absolute tolerance but not a "
"relative tolerance, only the absolute tolerance is considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:137
msgid ""
"In order to avoid inconsistent behavior, ``TypeError`` is raised for ``>``, "
"``>=``, ``<`` and ``<=`` comparisons. The example below illustrates the "
"problem::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:141
msgid ""
"assert approx(0.1) > 0.1 + 1e-10  # calls approx(0.1).__gt__(0.1 + 1e-10)\n"
"assert 0.1 + 1e-10 > approx(0.1)  # calls approx(0.1).__lt__(0.1 + 1e-10)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:144
msgid ""
"In the second example one expects ``approx(0.1).__le__(0.1 + 1e-10)`` to be "
"called. But instead, ``approx(0.1).__lt__(0.1 + 1e-10)`` is used to "
"comparison. This is because the call hierarchy of rich comparisons follows a "
"fixed behavior. `More information...`__"
msgstr ""

